{"title":"Climate Adaptation of Rice","status":"1","comment":"1","promote":"0","sticky":"0","body":{"und":[{"value":"[caption id=\"attachment_1312\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\" caption=\"Soy and rice cultivation in Northern Paraguay\"]<a href=\"http:\/\/www.usgs.gov\/blogs\/features\/files\/2011\/07\/rice_paraguay.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-1312\" src=\"http:\/\/www.usgs.gov\/blogs\/features\/files\/2011\/07\/rice_paraguay-300x154.jpg\" alt=\"Soy and rice cultivation in Northern Paraguay\" width=\"300\" height=\"154\" \/><\/a>[\/caption]\n\nNew USGS research shows that rice could become adapted to climate change and some catastrophic events by colonizing its seeds or plants with the spores of tiny naturally occurring fungi. The DNA of the rice plant itself is not changed; instead, researchers are re-creating what normally happens in nature.\n\n<a href=\"http:\/\/www.usgs.gov\/newsroom\/article.asp?ID=2852&amp;from=rss_home\">Learn more<\/a>","summary":null,"format":null}]},"field_images":{"und":[{"fid":"24130","uid":"31","filename":"rice_paraguay-300x154.jpg","uri":"public:\/\/rice_paraguay-300x154.jpg","filemime":"image\/jpeg","filesize":"17211","status":"1","timestamp":"1425492768","type":"image","uuid":"ae9902e9-3076-48a0-9b94-fb10cd6045f7","field_file_image_alt_text":[],"field_file_image_title_text":[],"metadata":{"height":154,"width":300},"alt":"","title":"","display":"1","description":null}]},"country":["United States of America"],"mm_tags":["biology","Climate Change","rice"],"article_type":["Featured Story"],"release_date":{"und":[{"value":"1310651250","timezone":"UTC","timezone_db":"UTC","date_type":"datestamp"}]},"contacts":[],"subtitle":[]}